        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">Dated on the basis of CD’s statement that he has had his lens altered. An entry in his Account Book (Down House MS) for 24 October reads: ‘Alteration of Microscope 3s. 6d.’</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">Hooker had provided drawings of barnacles, including <hi rend="italic">Cryptophialus</hi> <hi rend="italic">minutus</hi> (see n. 3, below), which CD used in <hi rend="italic">Living</hi> <hi rend="italic">Cirripedia</hi> (1854), see p. 566 n. Hooker’s drawings have not been found but some of CD’s original figures, dating from the <hi rend="italic">Beagle</hi> voyage, are in DAR 29.3: 72.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3"><hi rend="italic">Cryptophialus minutus</hi>, which CD originally called <hi rend="italic">Arthrobalanus</hi>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f4">No such paper has been found although CD evidently intended to publish one (see ‘Journal’; <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1581.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Correspondence</hi></ref> vol. 3, Appendix II). The results of his researches were eventually published in <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4838.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Living Cirripedia</hi> (1854): </ref>563–86.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f5"><ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_1104.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Burmeister 1834</ref>.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f6">Possibly an allusion to the small triangular points that cover the external membrane of <hi rend="italic">Cryptophialus</hi> (see <ref target="../bibliographies/bibl_4838.xml" resp="#mjhawkins"><hi rend="italic">Living Cirripedia</hi> (1854)</ref>, plate 23, figure 3), which resemble <hi rend="italic">Cheirotherium</hi> footprints.</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f7"><ref target="../nameregs/nameregs_35.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">Alexander James Adie</ref>, an optician and instrument-maker in Edinburgh.</note>
        </div>        
            
